                <!-- Technology Section -->
                <section class="about-section">
                    <div class="section-header">
                        <div class="section-icon">
                            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="32" height="32" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                                <rect x="2" y="3" width="20" height="14" rx="2" ry="2"></rect>
                                <line x1="8" y1="21" x2="16" y2="21"></line>
                                <line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12" y2="21"></line>
                            </svg>
                        </div>
                        <h2 class="section-title" data-i18n="OurTechnology">Our Technology</h2>
                    </div>
                    <p class="section-content" data-i18n="OurTechnologyDesc">
                        We leverage cutting-edge technology and partnerships with leading weather data providers to ensure the accuracy and reliability of our information. Our platform is built using modern web technologies to deliver fast, responsive, and accessible weather information.
                    </p>
                    <p class="section-content">
                        Our live weather and forecast data is sourced from established meteorological data providers, including the OpenWeatherMap service, which aggregates observations from weather stations, satellites, and radar around the globe. When you search for a location, we resolve it using trusted geocoding services so that a city name, postal code, or set of coordinates all point to the right place on the map. We then present current conditions — temperature, feels-like temperature, humidity, wind speed, and more — alongside a multi-day forecast.
                    </p>
                    <p class="section-content">
                        Because weather changes constantly, we refresh data frequently and cache it responsibly to keep the site fast without serving stale information. The interface is fully responsive, so it works just as well on a phone as on a desktop, and we optimise aggressively for page speed and Core Web Vitals so that checking the weather never feels like a chore.
                    </p>
                </section>

                <!-- Data & Accuracy Section -->
                <section class="about-section">
                    <div class="section-header">
                        <div class="section-icon">
                            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="32" height="32" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                                <path d="M22 12h-4l-3 9L9 3l-3 9H2"></path>
                            </svg>
                        </div>
                        <h2 class="section-title">A Note on Accuracy</h2>
                    </div>
                    <p class="section-content">
                        We work hard to provide the most accurate weather information possible, but it is important to be transparent: no weather forecast is ever perfect. Forecasting is a probabilistic science, and accuracy naturally decreases the further into the future a prediction reaches. Short-range forecasts of one to three days are highly reliable, while longer-range outlooks are best treated as general guidance. For critical decisions and during severe weather, we always encourage you to also consult your official national or regional meteorological service. You can read more about how this works in our guide on <a href="/Article/weather-forecasting">how weather forecasting works</a>.
                    </p>
                </section>

